We have some users which are unable to run our game on 32bit Windows systems.

The problem seems to be the OpenGL bindings. Every functions throw a `PInvokeStackImbalance`.

@dellis1972 any clue?

While reviewing some of the code for Ray.Intersects(BoundingBox), I found this snippet near line 130:

```
            // having a positive tMin and a negative tMax means the ray is inside the box
            // we expect the intesection distance to be 0 in that case
            if ((tMin.HasValue && tMin < 0) && tMax > 0) return 0;

            // a negative tMin means that the intersection point is behind the ray's origin
            // we discard these as not hitting the AABB
            if (tMin < 0) return null;
```

Notice that tMin is checked for being negative twice and the comment says that the value should be positive for the first check. Is this correct? If not, here's a snippet that should clear up the first line plus a small spelling fix in the comment (intersection).

```
            // we expect the intersection distance to be 0 in that case
            if ((tMin.HasValue && tMin > 0) && tMax < 0) return 0;
```

Greetings,

Right now it is not possible to modify default bound state, i.e. if you do
`GraphicsDevice.BlendState.BlendFactor = Color.Red`
it'll throw an exception ("You cannot modify the blend state after it has been bound to the graphics device!").
So if you want to modify only blend factor(keeping other blend state parameters), you have to do following:

```
var state = GraphicsDevice.BlendState.Clone();
state.BlendFactor = Color.Red;
GraphicsDevice.BlendState = state;
```

Probably more correct approach is to mark the bound blend state(or any other state such as RasterizerState) as dirty on any parameter change and then reapply it before next render call.

I.e. solution that will allow changing BlendFactor of bound state would involve following steps:
1. Add method invalidating blend state to GraphicsDevice:

   ```
   internal void InvalidateBlendState()
   {
       _blendStateDirty = true;
   }
   ```
2. Make sure BlendState.GraphicsDevice is set when the state is bound.
3. Call InvalidateBlendState when BlendFactor is changed:

   ```
   public Color BlendFactor
   {
     get { return _blendFactor; }
         set
         {
           if (value == _blendFactor) {
             return;
           }

           _blendFactor = value;
           GraphicsDevice.InvalidateBlendState();
         }
   }
   ```

**P.S. Thanks for your work! MonoGame is great not only because it is game engine, but also because it is unique source of experience of how to operate the gaming hardware on C#.**
